\frac{1}{4} \times \frac{4}{51} = \frac{1}{51}
\]</think> <answer>The probability is $\frac{1}{51}$.</answer>

You need to deal with conditional probability. The second card is independent of the first (well, if the first card is not an ace of diamonds), so $\ (\text{Pr(ace of diamonds on first draw})\ )\ (\text{Pr(ace on second draw})\ )$. The probability of the ace of diamonds on the first draw is $\52^{-1}$, but the probability of the ace on the second draw depends on whether you drew an ace of diamonds on the first draw or not. This means that the ace of diamonds will be included in the total number of draws for later draws (for example, if you drew the ace of diamonds, then $\text{Pr(ace on second draw}) \ = \ \51^{-} \ )$. So we need to calculate both cases. $
